The paper deals with the computational power of machines, which is a central topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The concept of self-specifying machines is related to the theory of computation and automata, which falls under the category of computer engineering (cs.CE). The paper also involves the study of languages and reductions, which are fundamental concepts in formal language theory and logic (cs.LO). The use of reductions and complexity classes suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the study of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper involves the use of information theory, which is a subfield of computer science that deals with the quantification, storage, and communication of information (cs.IT).
